Y by Adventure10, Mango247bashy in test solLet $\sin{x} = y$. Then $$\sin{x}+\sin{3x}+\sin{5x} = y+3y-4y^3+\sin(2x + 3x)=4y-4y^3+\sin{2x}\cos{3x}+\sin{3x}\cos{2x}$$$$=4y-4y^3+(2\sin{x}\cos{x})(4\cos^3{x}-3\cos{x})+(3\sin{x}-4\sin^3{x})(1-2\sin^2{x})$$$$=4y-4y^3+(2y\sqrt{1-y^2})(4\sqrt{(1-y^2)^3}-3\sqrt{1-y^2})+(3y-4y^3)(1-2y^2)$$$$=4y-4y^3+8y(1-y^2)^2-6y(1-y^2)+3y-6y^3-4y^3+8y^5$$$$=8y^5-14y^3+7y+(8y)(y^4-2y^2+1)-6y+6y^3$$$$=16y^5-24y^3+9y = y(16y^4-24y^2+9)=y(4y^2-3)^2$$We want to maximize this function, so we take the derivative (with product rule) and set it to $0$: $$16y^2(4y^2-3)+(4y^2-3)^2=(4y^2-3)(20y^2-3)=0\Rightarrow y^2=\frac{3}{4}, \frac{3}{20}$$Plugging these values in, we get $y(4y^2-3)^2=0, \sqrt{\frac{3}{20}}(\frac{12}{5})^2$. Clearly $0$ isn't correct, so the answer is $\sqrt{\frac{3}{20}}(\frac{12}{5})^2=\frac{\sqrt{15}}{10}(\frac{144}{25})=\boxed{\frac{72\sqrt{15}}{125}}$



