problems.text:
Recall that in any row of Pascal's Triangle, the first and last elements of the row are $1$ and each other element in the row is the sum of the two elements above it from the previous row.  With this in mind, define the $\textit{Pascal Squared Triangle}$ as follows:


In the $n^{\text{th}}$ row, where $n\geq 1$, the first and last elements of the row equal $n^2$;
Each other element is the sum of the two elements directly above it.



The first few rows of the Pascal Squared Triangle are shown below.



\[\begin{array}{c@{\hspace{7em}}
c@{\hspace{2pt}}c@{\hspace{2pt}}c@{\hspace{4pt}}c@{\hspace{2pt}}
c@{\hspace{2pt}}c@{\hspace{2pt}}c@{\hspace{2pt}}c@{\hspace{3pt}}c@{\hspace{2pt}}
c@{\hspace{2pt}}c} \vspace{4pt}
\text{Row 1: } & & & & & & 1 & & & & & \\\vspace{4pt}
\text{Row 2: } & & & & & 4 & & 4 & & & & \\\vspace{4pt}
\text{Row 3: } & & & & 9 & & 8 & & 9 & & & \\\vspace{4pt}
\text{Row 4: } & & &16& &17& &17& & 16& & \\\vspace{4pt}
\text{Row 5: } & &25 & &33& &34 & &33 & &25 &
\end{array}\]Let $S_n$ denote the sum of the entries in the $n^{\text{th}}$ row.  For how many integers $1\leq n\leq 10^6$ is $S_n$ divisible by $13$?

Misha is currently taking a Complexity Theory exam, but he seems to have forgotten a lot of the material! In the question, he is asked to fill in the following boxes with $\subseteq$ and $\subsetneq$ to identify the relationship between different complexity classes: $$\mathsf{NL}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{P}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{NP}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{PH}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{PSPACE}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf {EXP}$$and $$\mathsf{coNL}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{P}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{coNP}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\  \mathsf{PH}$$Luckily, he remembers that $\mathsf{P} 
eq \mathsf{EXP}$, $\mathsf{NL} 
eq \mathsf{PSPACE}$, $\mathsf{coNL} 
eq \mathsf{PSPACE}$, and $\mathsf{NP} 
eq \mathsf{coNP}\implies \mathsf{P}
eq \mathsf{NP} \land \mathsf{P}
eq \mathsf{coNP}$.

How many ways are there for him to fill in the boxes so as not to contradict what he remembers?
